; demo-005-start-directive.a
; Chapter 3: Assembly Language Basics
; Concept: Using .start to specify the entry point when layout order matters.
;
; NEW CONCEPTS:
;   .start <label>  — tell the assembler where execution should begin.
;                     Without .start, execution begins at address 0 (first
;                     instruction in the file). If a subroutine comes first,
;                     the CPU will execute it before main — usually a bug.
;
; PROBLEM (without .start):
;   If greet is defined before main, the CPU starts at greet, executes ret
;   with an uninitialized lr, and jumps to a garbage address → crash/loop.
;
; SOLUTION: .start main tells the assembler to record main as the entry point
;   in the .e file header, so execution always begins there regardless of
;   where main sits in the file.
;
; C equivalent:
;   void greet() { printf("Hello\n"); }
;   int main() { greet(); greet(); }

          .start main      ; <-- entry point declaration

; ---- subroutine (defined BEFORE main — safe only because of .start) ----
greet:    lea  r0, msg
          sout r0
          ret

msg:      .string "Hello\n"

; ---- main (entry point) ----
main:     bl   greet
          bl   greet
          halt
